<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-685-928  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 685 928.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DBMS  August 1990 v3 n9 p28(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple's link to corporate data. (Data Access Language providesdesktop link to host data) (interview)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Strehlo, Kevin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Network Innovations Pres James Groff believes that Data AccessLanguage allows microcomputer users the best access to host data.andO;He feels that Structured Query Language (SQL) is not well-suitedfor a microcomputer link to host data because there is no standardfront end processor and because SQL is not designed to cope withhost system intelligence.andP;  Data Access Language, on the otherhand, allows host-level processing to be isolated from the frontend terminal and provides data base brand independence.andP;  Appleacquired Network Innovations in Spring 1988, and plans toincorporate Data Access Language into its System 7 operatingsystem.andP;  Groff believes that Apple provides an advantage byyielding uniformity across hardware lines, but the market iscurrently too segmented to take advantage of unified solutions.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. Network Innovations (officials and employees).andO;Topic:     Data Base Management SystemsData Base LanguagesStructured Query Language.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   James Groff. (portrait)Person:    Groff, James (interviews).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>